            "The modern era of the chair is defined by Edwin Barker, who was appointed principal bass in 1977 at age 22 — making him the youngest principal player in the orchestra's history.[2] He held the position for forty-eight years, retiring at the close of the 2024–25 season.[3]",
            "Barker grew up in Plattsburgh, New York, where he started bass in fourth grade through a mandatory school string program.[4] By fifteen he was performing professionally with the Vermont Symphony and the Albany Symphony.[4] He studied with Frederick Zimmermann at a summer camp at Crane School of Music, then with Peter Mercurio on the West Coast, and ultimately with Henry Portnoi at New England Conservatory.[5] He graduated NEC in 1976 with honors and the Chadwick Medal, and was a Tanglewood Fellow in 1975, receiving the Delson Award for Most Outstanding Instrumentalist.[2] That same year, he won a position with the Chicago Symphony Orchestra under Georg Solti. While at the CSO, he auditioned for and won the BSO principal chair.[5]",
            "Barker played French bow — a lineage traceable through his teacher Portnoi back to Anton Torello at the Curtis Institute, who is credited with establishing the French bow hold in American orchestral bass playing. His tonebase course, \"The French Bow Arm,\" describes a suspended, shoulder-led bow stroke. \"A beautiful bass tone doesn't come from force,\" Barker has said. \"It comes from freedom.\"[6] He developed what he calls a \"carried detaché\" — a stroke unique to the Boston school in which the bow begins its motion in the air, \"like an airplane landing.\"[7]",
            "His primary orchestral instrument has not been publicly identified, but the Navona Records biography for his 2024 album states that he \"played a double bass that was handed down to him from his predecessor Henry Portnoi.\"[8] Whether this was the Vilho Arvi bass that Portnoi commissioned — discussed below — has not been confirmed.",
            "In 1981, Barker inaugurated the BSO's centennial season as soloist in the Koussevitzky Double Bass Concerto — the first time in the orchestra's history that a bass concerto soloist appeared on a BSO subscription series.[9] The Boston Globe wrote: \"Not only does Edwin Barker have what it takes to lead the Boston Symphony double bass section; in a solo capacity he can make that famously unwieldy instrument bearable, plausible; nay, downright compelling… What class!\"[9] In 2001, Seiji Ozawa invited him to perform Bruch's Kol Nidrei with the BSO. The Globe's review: \"Barker offered the music as prayer, and made of his huge instrument a still, small voice asking eternal questions and responding with timeless answers.\"[9]",
            "As a member of the Boston Symphony Chamber Players, Barker recorded extensively — including the Schubert Trout Quintet and the Stravinsky L'Histoire du Soldat — and received a Grammy nomination in 2012.[2] His solo discography includes Three Sonatas for Double Bass (Boston Records), Concerti for Double Bass with the Pro Arte Chamber Orchestra conducted by Gunther Schuller (GM Recordings),[10] the Harbison Concerto for Bass Viol with the Boston Modern Orchestra Project (BMOP Sound),[11] and Basso Profundo (Navona Records, 2024), featuring his own arrangement of Bach's Cello Suite No. 5 and Weinberg's Sonata Op. 108 for solo double bass.[8] The GM Recordings disc includes a live performance of Tom Johnson's Failing — a piece in which the bassist must sustain a running spoken narrative while playing increasingly difficult music — recorded at Harvard's Sanders Theater on November 26, 2000.[10]",
            "On July 26, 2024 — the 150th anniversary of Serge Koussevitzky's birth — Barker returned to Tanglewood to perform the Koussevitzky Concerto one final time, this time on Koussevitzky's own historical bass, loaned for the occasion by the International Society of Bassists.[12] The instrument, slightly smaller than a standard orchestral bass, had been bequeathed to Gary Karr by Koussevitzky's widow Olga in 1962 and is now held by the ISB.[13] Barker later gave a public lecture at the Boston Public Library in November 2024, titled \"Koussevitzky, the Double Bass, and the BSO,\" examining how Koussevitzky's background as a virtuoso bassist shaped the orchestra's sound.[14]",
            "An associate professor at Boston University,[11] Barker served as chairman of instrumental and orchestral studies at the Tanglewood Music Center from 2004 to 2012.[2] In 2025 he received the International Society of Bassists' Distinguished Achievement Award — the ISB's highest honor, given biennially for lifetime accomplishment.[15] George Speed, presenting the award, said: \"For 48 years, Ed has led the Boston Symphony bass section with artistry, grace, and supreme command of his craft.\"[15]",
