    bio: "Orin O'Brien made history on the night Leonard Bernstein hired her to join the New York Philharmonic in 1966 — becoming the first woman to hold a full-time position in the orchestra. Born on June 7, 1935, in Hollywood, California, to film actors George O'Brien and Marguerite Churchill, she began on piano at age six and picked up the double bass in high school after watching her school orchestra perform Saint-Saëns' Rondo Capriccioso — the conductor offered her a borrowed bass if she would take six months of lessons. Her first teacher was Milton Kestenbaum; she then studied with Herman Reinshagen in California before coming to New York in 1954 to study with Frederick Zimmermann at The Juilliard School. Zimmermann himself insisted she audition for the Philharmonic.\n\nBefore joining the NYP she was a member of the New York City Ballet Orchestra (1956–1966) and performed as a Metropolitan Opera freelancer for five years, including in Bernstein's Falstaff in 1964. She also performed with the American Symphony Orchestra under Leopold Stokowski and appears on the first recording of Gunther Schuller's Quartet for Double Basses. She auditioned for the Philharmonic three times before being hired by Bernstein. She held The Secular Society Chair and retired in 2021 after 55 years of service.\n\nDuring her career she gave the U.S. premiere of Ginastera's Variaciones Concertantes in 1962 and recorded with Pablo Casals at the Marlboro Music Festival. She served on the faculties of The Juilliard School — co-chairing the double bass department from 1992 to 2002 — the Manhattan School of Music, and Mannes College of Music, and received the Manhattan School of Music President's Medal for Distinguished Faculty Service in 2010.\n\nThe documentary The Only Girl in the Orchestra, directed by her niece Molly O'Brien, premiered on Netflix on December 4, 2024, and won the Academy Award for Best Documentary Short Film at the 97th Academy Awards on March 2, 2025. O'Brien initially declined to be the subject of the film before agreeing.",
