    initials: "EB", color: "#6E8FC8",
    bio: "Edwin Barker was appointed Principal Bass of the Boston Symphony Orchestra in 1976 at age 22 — holding the Harold D. Hodgkinson Chair — having graduated with honors from New England Conservatory that same year (earning the Chadwick Medal), where he studied with Henry Portnoi, while already a member of the Chicago Symphony Orchestra under Sir Georg Solti. He became the youngest principal player in BSO history. He retired at the close of the 2024–25 season after 48 years of service.\n\nGrowing up in Plattsburgh, New York, Barker began bass at age nine through a mandatory school string program. By fifteen he was performing professionally with the Vermont Symphony and the Albany Symphony. His teachers included Angelo LaMariana (Plattsburgh), Frederick Zimmermann (Crane School of Music summer camp), Peter Mercurio (Los Angeles), Richard Stephan, and David Perleman (Cleveland Orchestra principal, at Blossom Festival). He attended the Music Academy of the West for three summers and was a Tanglewood Fellow in 1975, receiving the Delson Award for Most Outstanding Instrumentalist. In January 1976, as a New England Conservatory senior, he performed as a substitute with the New York Philharmonic before winning a permanent seat with the Chicago Symphony.\n\nAs soloist with the BSO he gave world premieres of James Yannatos' Concerto for Contrabass — written for him — and Theodore Antoniou's Concertino for Contrabass and Chamber Orchestra, and the joint world premiere of John Harbison's Concerto for Bass Viol at Tanglewood's 2007 Festival of Contemporary Music. He also gave the New England premiere of Gunther Schuller's Concerto for Double Bass and Chamber Orchestra. He inaugurated the BSO's centennial season with a performance of the Koussevitzky Concerto; the Boston Globe praised the performance for possessing 'everything that makes great artistry.' In 2001, Seiji Ozawa invited him to perform Bruch's Kol Nidrei with the BSO. In July 1995 he was chosen by Sir Georg Solti to lead the bass section of the United Nations' Musicians of the World ensemble.\n\nHis solo recordings include Three Sonatas for Double Bass (Boston Records), James Yannatos' Variations for Solo Contrabass (Albany Records), Concerti for Double Bass (GM Recordings — including works by Schuller and Antoniou, and a live recording of Tom Johnson's Failing at Harvard's Sanders Theater), John Harbison's Concerto for Bass Viol and Orchestra (BMOP Sound), George Perle's Monody II and Fred Lerdahl's Fire and Ice — a work commissioned by the Tanglewood Music Center for its 75th anniversary and written for high soprano and contrabass, performed with soprano Elizabeth Fischborn (Bridge Records) — and Basso Profundo (Navona Records, July 2024), featuring his own arrangement of Bach's Cello Suite No. 5 BWV 1011 and Weinberg's Sonata Op. 108 for solo double bass. He also recorded chamber music with the Boston Symphony Chamber Players that received a Grammy nomination in 2012.\n\nAn associate professor at Boston University's College of Fine Arts (teaching double bass, orchestral techniques, and chamber music), he served as chairman of instrumental and orchestral studies at the Tanglewood Music Center from 2004 to 2012, and taught at the National Orchestral Institute at the University of Maryland. He received the NEC Outstanding Alumni Award and was named the recipient of the International Society of Bassists' Distinguished Achievement Award in 2025 — the ISB's highest honor, given biennially for lifetime accomplishment. Max Zeugner and David Grossman of the New York Philharmonic each studied with Barker during their formative years.",
