    initials: "EL", color: "#4A7BA7",
    bio: "Eugene Levinson served as Principal Bass of the New York Philharmonic from 1985 until his retirement in 2011 — a 26-year tenure that transformed the section and produced a generation of principal bassists who now lead major American orchestras. Born in Kiev to a musical family, he earned his doctorate at the Leningrad Conservatory and became its youngest faculty member at twenty-nine, while serving as principal bass of the Leningrad Chamber Orchestra for thirteen years and playing in the Leningrad Philharmonic for nearly sixteen years.\n\nHe emigrated in 1977, encountered Zubin Mehta in Rome, and the day after arriving in Minneapolis auditioned for the Minnesota Orchestra on a borrowed instrument — and won the principal chair. Mehta appointed him Principal Bass of the New York Philharmonic in 1985, putting him on a European tour immediately, before Levinson had attended a single pre-tour rehearsal. His solo appearances with the NYP included the Koussevitzky Concerto with Mehta, the Tubin Concerto with Kurt Masur, and a 2004 PBS Live from Lincoln Center broadcast of Mozart's Per questa bella mano with Thomas Quasthoff and Riccardo Muti. He received the ISB Distinguished Special Recognition Award in 2003.\n\nAt Juilliard, where he joined the faculty in 1985 and co-chaired the bass department from 1992 to 2003, his students include Isaac Trapkus and Rion Wentworth of the current NYP section. His publications include The School of Agility (Carl Fischer) — called 'a stellar contribution to the field of bass pedagogy' by American String Teacher — a re-edition of the Simandl Concerto, a new edition of a Haydn cello concerto, and a guide to orchestral excerpts for Boosey & Hawkes.",
