    initials: "HR", color: "#8B4A8C",
    bio: "Harold 'Hal' Robinson served as Principal Bass of the Philadelphia Orchestra from 1995 until his retirement in 2022, holding the A. Margaret Bok Chair in Double Bass Studies at the Curtis Institute throughout that tenure and training a generation of bassists who now populate major orchestras across the country — among them Joseph Conyers, Gabriel Polinsky, Tobias Vigneau, and Nathaniel West, all current Philadelphia Orchestra section members. Born on July 29, 1952, in Houston, Texas, he grew up in a family of seven professional string players: his father was principal bass of the Houston Symphony, his mother a violinist with the same orchestra, and all four of his siblings — cellists Sharon (of the Kalichstein-Laredo-Robinson Trio) and Keith Jr. (founding member, Miami String Quartet) and violinists Erica and Kim — pursued professional performance careers.\n\nRobinson studied at Northwestern University and the Peabody Conservatory. From 1975 to 1977 he was principal bass of the Albuquerque Symphony (now the New Mexico Symphony Orchestra) and performed in the Santa Fe Opera Orchestra. In 1977 he joined the Houston Symphony as assistant principal bass, and in 1985 Mstislav Rostropovich appointed him principal bass of the National Symphony Orchestra, a post he held until 1995. He was a prizewinner at the 1982 Isle of Man Solo Competition and appeared as concerto soloist with the Philadelphia Orchestra, the New York Philharmonic, the Houston Symphony, and other ensembles. He gave recitals and master classes throughout the United States, Korea, Japan, and Europe, including as faculty of the Pacific Music Festival in Sapporo.\n\nHe continues to teach at The Juilliard School and received the International Society of Bassists' Distinguished Achievement Award in 2023.",
