    initials: "MS", color: "#6B5A8C",
    bio: "Michael Shahan retired from the Philadelphia Orchestra in 2021 after 57 years of service — one of the longest tenures in the orchestra's history — having joined in 1964, been named Assistant Principal Bass in 1970, and risen to Associate Principal Bass in 1987. Born in Washington D.C. in 1940, he studied at the Curtis Institute of Music and played with the National Symphony for two seasons in 1961–62 before arriving in Philadelphia.\n\nAmong his most distinguished moments came in September 1973, when he was one of 104 Philadelphia Orchestra musicians who traveled to the People's Republic of China — the first American orchestra ever to perform there — on a history-making cultural diplomacy mission arranged just nineteen months after President Nixon's own opening of relations with Beijing. The tour, documented in the film Beethoven in Beijing, occurred during the Cultural Revolution when Western classical music was banned in China; Shahan was one of only three musicians still active in the orchestra decades later who had made that journey. He was awarded the C. Hartman Kuhn Award in 1987 for distinguished service to the Orchestra — the ensemble's highest musician honor.\n\nA musician of unusual range, he maintained parallel careers as a chamber musician with the Philadelphia Chamber Ensemble, the Philadelphia Jazz Quintet, and as co-music director of the Amerita Chamber Players. He performed on viola da gamba with the American Society of Ancient Instruments. He taught double bass at Temple University's Boyer College of Music and Dance (formerly the New School of Music) for 35 years.",
