    id: "phi-conyers", orchestraId: "phi", name: "Joseph Conyers",
    role: "Principal Bass", since: 2010, appointedSince: 2023, chair: "Carole and Emilio Gravagno Chair",
    initials: "JC", color: "#8B4A8C",
    bio: "Joseph Conyers became Principal Bass of the Philadelphia Orchestra in May 2023, having spent over a decade building toward the role within the same section — joining in 2010 as assistant principal, serving as acting associate principal from 2017, and winning the audition after competing against more than 100 international bassists. At the time of his initial hiring in 2010, he was the first Black musician to join the Philadelphia Orchestra in 36 years; as principal he is one of the few Black principal players in a major American orchestra.\n\nGrown up in Savannah, Georgia — a city with a small music community where he was the only bass player in local youth ensembles — Conyers attended the Brevard Music Festival in North Carolina and the Boston University Tanglewood Institute before enrolling at the Curtis Institute of Music, where he studied with Harold Robinson and Edgar Meyer. Before joining Philadelphia he served as principal bass of the Grand Rapids Symphony for three and a half years and performed four summers with the Santa Fe Opera Orchestra, as well as a tenure with the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra. He appeared on the radio program From the Top in 1999 during its second pilot season.\n\nHis awards include Second Prize at the 2004 Sphinx Competition, the inaugural Young Alumni Award from Curtis (2015), the C. Hartman Kuhn Award (2018), the Theodore L. Kesselman Award (2018), recognition in Musical America's 30 Top Professionals (2018), the Sphinx Organization's Medal of Excellence (2019), and the American String Teachers Association Artist Teacher Award (2024). In 2024 he was named the Orchestra's Education and Community Ambassador, a newly endowed position recognizing his work as founder and vision advisor of Project 440, founded in 2007. He is Music Director of Philadelphia's All-City Orchestra, serves on the double bass faculty of The Juilliard School, and is a board member of the Boston University Tanglewood Institute. He has been an artist of the Chamber Music Society of Lincoln Center for several years. In the 2025–26 season he makes his Philadelphia Orchestra solo debut performing Tan Dun's Contrabass Concerto: Wolf Totem. He is co-host of the podcast Tacet No More with Philadelphia Orchestra cellist Yumi Kendall and was featured on PBS's Articulate in 2021.\n\nHis instrument is an 1802 double bass by the Sicilian-born English luthier Vincenzo Panormo, which he has named Norma. He acquired it in April 2007 after first encountering it in Grand Rapids, Michigan, in autumn 2005; a benefactor named Edith Blodgett donated funds to the Grand Rapids Symphony that enabled him to purchase it.",
    instruments: [{ name: "1802 Vincenzo Panormo double bass \"Norma\"", maker: "Vincenzo Panormo, London, England", era: "1802", story: true, storyTitle: "A bass called Norma", detail: "Conyers first encountered this bass in Grand Rapids, Michigan, in autumn 2005 but could not afford it at the time. A benefactor named Edith Blodgett donated funds to the Grand Rapids Symphony in April 2007, enabling Conyers to purchase the instrument. He named it Norma, continuing a personal tradition of naming his basses (previous instruments were called Jackie, Gabby, and Reiley). Vincenzo Panormo (1734–1813) was born in Sicily and worked principally in London, where he built instruments in the tradition of the great Cremonese makers." }],
