    bio: "Tobias Vigneau joined the Philadelphia Orchestra as Assistant Principal Bass in September 2024. Born and raised in Albuquerque, New Mexico, he began violin at age five and switched to double bass at ten, drawn to the instrument through jazz trio recordings — a connection deepened by having two jazz piano-playing grandfathers. His parents are professional orchestral musicians: his father Kevin Vigneau is principal oboe of Santa Fe Pro Musica and the New Mexico Philharmonic, and his mother Kim Fredenburgh is principal violist of Santa Fe Pro Musica and the Santa Fe Symphony. In 2020 Vigneau and his parents formed tRio Grande, an ensemble of oboe, viola, and bass that has commissioned works from composers including Sérgio Azevedo, Miguel del Águila, Mariano Morales, David Dean Mendoza, and Durwynne Hsieh.\n\nHe earned his Bachelor of Music from the Curtis Institute of Music in 2024, where he studied with Harold Robinson and Edgar Meyer and served as principal bass of the Curtis Symphony Orchestra in his final year. He was the double bass fellow at the Marlboro Music Festival in 2024. His festival appearances also include two summers at the Tanglewood Music Center (2022 and 2023) — where he participated in the Festival of Contemporary Music and gave the North American premiere of George Benjamin's opera Lessons in Love and Violence — and orchestral fellowships at the Aspen Music Festival and School in 2019 and 2021, studying with Albert Laszlo and Timothy Pitts.\n\nHe has appeared as concerto soloist with the New Mexico Philharmonic as the 2018 Jackie McGehee Young Artist's Competition first-prize winner and the 2023 Santa Fe Symphony Concerto Competition Senior Division winner, performing Bottesini's B-minor Concerto. He also performed with the Montreal Symphony, Santa Fe Pro Musica Chamber Orchestra, the Santa Fe Symphony, Symphony in C, and ChatterABQ.",
