    id: "phi-rosengard", orchestraId: "phi", name: "Duane Rosengard",
    role: "Section Bass", since: 1986, chair: null,
    initials: "DR", color: "#6E8A7A",
    bio: "Duane Rosengard joined the Philadelphia Orchestra bass section in December 1986. Born in Chicago in 1960, he began playing double bass at age eleven and studied at Interlochen Arts Academy and the Cleveland Institute of Music. He previously performed with the Rochester Philharmonic, the Buffalo Philharmonic, and the Orquesta Sinfónica de Veracruz in Mexico.\n\nParallel to his orchestral career, Rosengard has built a second career as an instrument scholar, publishing extensively on historical stringed instruments in journals and encyclopedias in Italy, England, Germany, and the United States and contributing to Strings and Strad magazines. His books include Cremonese Double Basses (1992); The Stradivari Legacy (1998, co-authored); Giuseppe Guarneri del Gesù (1998; Mandarin edition published in Beijing, 2017); Giovanni Battista Guadagnini (2000); The Late Cremonese Violin Makers (2002, co-authored); Carlo Bergonzi (2010); and Paolo Diana \"detto Spagnoletti\" (2018, co-authored with Elliott Golub). He holds associate membership in the American Federation of Violin and Bow Makers, serves on the Scientific Committee of the Ente Triennale Internazionale degli Strumenti ad Arco in Cremona, Italy, and lectures at the Violin Society of America and the International Society of Bassists. He is currently preparing a monograph on the Parisian bowmakers the Tourte brothers.\n\nWith his childhood friend Mark Kindig and luthier Zachary S. Martin of Rhode Island, Rosengard co-founded a project partnering with Penn Medicine researchers to CT-scan approximately twenty of the world's finest historical double basses. The project's primary focus is measuring internal air volume — which the team identifies as directly related to an instrument's sonority and power — and wood density.",
